Role: Act as a Senior Creative Technologist and Lead 3D Developer specializing in WebGL, Three.js, and spatial installation design.
Context: We are building a large-scale interactive digital art installation for a Sustainable Energy Company, to be displayed on a massive LED wall in a city center.
Source Material: I have a basic Three.js prototype (provided below) that uses standard geometry and basic post-processing. It currently renders a generic terrain with cylinders and connection lines.
The Objective: Refactor and significantly upgrade this code into a modern, high-fidelity interactive experience that visualizes the ecosystem of sustainable energy. The scene must tell the story of energy generated by nature (Wind/Solar) flowing into a bustling city.
Design & Technical Requirements:
Modern Stack:
Convert the code to use ES Modules (import maps).
Upgrade to a recent version of Three.js (r150+).
Visual Overhaul (The "Art" Aspect):
Aesthetic: Move away from the dark/abstract "hacker" look. Aim for a "Future Solarpunk" or "Clean Energy" aesthetic—ethereal, glowing, organic, using a palette of whites, cyans (wind), golds (solar), and lush greens.
Lighting: Implement high-quality lighting (Environment maps/HDR) to make materials look premium.
Specific Asset Replacement (Procedural or Primitive-based):
Wind Turbines: Replace the random cylinders with instanced geometry representing Wind Turbines. Crucial: Animate the blades rotation.
Solar Farms: Replace specific clusters with flat, grid-like geometry representing Solar Panels that reflect the "sun."
The City: Create a central cluster of geometry that represents a "City Center" (the consumer of energy).
Advanced Flow Visualization:
The "arcs" currently just sit there. Rewrite the flow system to visualize Energy Transfer.
Use animated textures or a custom ShaderMaterial on the tubes so pulses of light travel from the Turbines/Panels towards the City.
Interactivity (Installation Mode):
Since this is for a public installation, the interaction should be intuitive.
Mouse/Hand Interaction: When the cursor moves, it should influence the "Wind" (making turbines spin faster) or the "Sun" (changing lighting direction).
Auto-Camera: Maintain a slow, cinematic orbit (as people might just watch it pass by), but allow manual override.
Code Quality:
Use InstancedMesh for performance (thousands of objects).
Keep the code in a single file (for ease of prototyping now) but structure it cleanly with classes or distinct setup functions.
The Narrative to Visualize:
"Nature provides the power. We harness it. The City thrives."
Input Code to Refactor:
